"Bamberg A., Rosenthal Y., Paul A., Heslop D., Mulitza S., Rühlemann C., Schulz M.","Reduced North Atlantic central water formation in response to early Holocene ice-sheet melting",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","17", L17705,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL043878,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956716098&partnerID=40&md5=748cc6dc8d12837053f1aba348e5c9b5","MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany; Federal Institute for Geosciences and Natural Resources, Stilleweg 2, D-30655 Hannover, Germany; Institute for Marine and Coastal Sciences, Department of Geology, Rutgers University, 71 Dudley Rd., New Brunswick, NJ 08901-8525, United States","Bamberg, A., MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany, Federal Institute for Geosciences and Natural Resources, Stilleweg 2, D-30655 Hannover, Germany; Rosenthal, Y., Institute for Marine and Coastal Sciences, Department of Geology, Rutgers University, 71 Dudley Rd., New Brunswick, NJ 08901-8525, United States; Paul, A., MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany; Heslop, D., MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany; Mulitza, S., MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany; Rühlemann, C., Federal Institute for Geosciences and Natural Resources, Stilleweg 2, D-30655 Hannover, Germany; Schulz, M., MARUM Center for Marine Environmental Sciences, Faculty of Geosciences, University of Bremen, Klagenfurter Straße, D-28359 Bremen, Germany","Central waters of the North Atlantic are fundamental for ventilation of the upper ocean and are also linked to the strength of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC). Here, we show based on benthic foraminiferal Mg/Ca ratios, that during times of enhanced melting from the Laurentide Ice Sheet (LIS) between 9.0-8.5 thousand years before present (ka) the production of central waters weakened the upper AMOC resulting in a cooling over the Northern Hemisphere. Centered at 8.54 0.2 ka and 8.24 0.1 ka our dataset records two ∼150-year cooling events in response to the drainage of Lake Agassiz/Ojibway, indicating early slow-down of the upper AMOC in response to the initial freshwater flux into the subpolar gyre (SPG) followed by a more severe weakening of both the upper and lower branches of the AMOC at 8.2 ka. These results highlight the sensitivity of regional North Atlantic climate change to the strength of central-water overturning and exemplify the impact of both gradual and abrupt freshwater fluxes on eastern SPG surface water convection. In light of the possible future increase in Greenland Ice Sheet melting due to global warming these findings may help us to better constrain and possibly predict future North Atlantic climate change. © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Glacial geology; Glaciers; Global warming; Melting; Oceanography; Atlantic meridional overturning circulations; Data sets; Freshwater fluxes; Greenland Ice Sheet; Holocenes; Laurentide ice sheets; North Atlantic; Northern Hemispheres; Possible futures; Subpolar gyres; Upper ocean; Water convection; Water formation; Ice",,,,,,"Alley, R.B., Agustsdottir, A.M., The 8k event: Cause and consequences of a major Holocene abrupt climate change (2005) Quaternary Science Reviews, 24 (10-11), pp. 1123-1149. , DOI 10.1016/j.quascirev.2004.12.004, PII S0277379105000314; Badger, M.R., The diversity and coevolution of Rubisco, plastids, pyrenoids, and chloroplast-based CO<inf>2</inf>-concentrating mechanisms in algae (1998) Can. J. Bot., 76, pp. 1052-1071. , doi:10.1139/cjb-76-6-1052; Baldwin, 